english:
  title: Inscription for the Sacred Way Stele of King Hwan's Tomb at Jungneung, in the Enlightened Realm of Joseon
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the second year of my lord's reign, on the day Sinmi of the first moon of spring, he commanded his servant thus:

    "By humble virtue alone, I received Heaven's gracious mandate and early established this realm, relying upon the accumulated merit of my ancestors. I have reverently conferred posthumous titles upon four generations, elevating all to royal rank. You shall compose the inscription for my illustrious father's Jungneung tomb, that it may shine eternally for all ages to come."

    Your servant, receiving this command with trembling reverence, dared not decline, however meager his talents. I have long observed the words of Mencius: "In five hundred years, surely a sage-king shall arise." When the previous dynasty had nearly completed five centuries since its founder, King Wang, the mandate's decline had set in. As the line of the devoted king ended, a spurious monk's son named U falsely claimed the Wang surname and usurped the throne. Debauched and tyrannical, in the year Mujin he and his minister Choi Young recklessly mustered arms to invade the Celestial Empire's borders, bringing calamities upon the people beyond reckoning.

    At that moment, our present lord—then commanding the Right Military—upheld righteousness and turned back the armies. U recognized his crime and yielded the throne to his son Chang. The following year, the Emperor censured the succession of one not of Wang blood. Our lord, serving as attendant-minister, consulted with the generals and established Wang Yo, a collateral descendant of the Wang line, as ruler.

    From U's reign onward, power had rested in the hands of ambitious ministers. Officials and punishments were bought and sold; the court fell into chaos. Private lands were seized; mountains and fields were plundered. The very sinews of government unraveled, and corruption festered daily. The people sighed in misery, yearning day and night for righteous rule.

    When our lord assumed the position of prime minister, he swept away old corruptions and renewed the path of governance. He abolished the private land system to restore proper boundaries. He pruned the redundant bureaucracy to restore the dignity of office. He elevated the capable and virtuous, banishing the crooked and cruel. He wielded military might to repel barbarian incursions; he dispensed benevolent governance to enrich the people's livelihood. He restored order to law and ceremony, cultivating culture and rites. The people of the Three Hans loved him as a parent.

    Yet Yo, clouded in judgment and ignorant of greater matters, placed his trust in treacherous men and cast out the loyal and upright. Heeding the whispers of women and eunuchs, he corrupted the land system's integrity. Through favoritism, he undermined the merit of appointments. His edicts lacked consistency, destroying the realm's laws. His expenditures knew no restraint, draining the people's wealth. He believed the poisonous slanders of petty men and forgot our lord's labors of restoration. Together with his minister Jeong Mongju, he constantly plotted against him.

    Mongju secretly instigated his allies among the remonstrators to fabricate charges against the meritorious ministers and honest speakers, preparing to implicate our lord in false accusations. Chaos threatened beyond measure, and all the realm's people burned with indignation.

    On the sixteenth day of the seventh moon in the twenty-fifth year of Hongwu, fifty-two officials—including Left Minister Bae Geuk-ryeom and Right Minister Cho Jun—perceiving where Heaven's will lay and whither the people's hearts turned, proclaimed the greater righteousness. Without prior consultation, all the officials and elders as one urged our lord to ascend the throne. Though he demurred twice and thrice, the multitude's resolve grew ever firmer. He yielded at last and took the dragon seat. The merchants did not close their shops; the soldiers shed no blood. Within a single dawn, all grew clear and bright, and the people rejoiced greatly.

    Immediately, he dispatched the director of the secretariat to inform the imperial court. The Emperor issued a rescript: "The people of the Three Hans have honored the house of Lee; free from war's scourge, each enjoys the happiness Heaven bestows. This accords with the Celestial Will."

    Shortly after, the director returned with another imperial decree: "What name has the realm been given? Report with haste." Our lord commanded the Hanlin scholar Han Sang-jil to request a name. The Emperor bestowed the name Joseon, saying: "Accord with Heaven in shepherding the people; extend this glory forever to your descendants." Thus did he receive aid from both Heaven and man, fulfilling the saying that in five hundred years a true king arises.

    Your servant has reverently traced the lineage through the luminous records. In the renowned house of Jeonju, there was one called Sako, who served Silla and married the daughter of Military Commander Kim Un-ui, great-great-grandson of Taejong. They begat Attendant-Minister Ja-yeon. Ja-yeon begat Vice-Minister Cheon-sang. Cheon-sang begat Minister Kwang-hui. Kwang-hui begat Minister Ip-jeon. Ip-jeon begat Geung-hyu. Geung-hyu begat Yeom-sun. Yeom-sun begat Seung-sak. Seung-sak begat Chung-kyeong. Chung-kyeong begat Kyeong-yeong. Kyeong-yeong begat Chung-min. Chung-min begat [lost name]. From there came Gung-jin, who begat General Yong-bu. General Yong-bu begat Inner Attendant In. In married the daughter of Minister Mun Geuk-kyeom, begetting General Yang-mu. Yang-mu married the daughter of Supreme General Lee Kang-je, begetting Director of Ming-ju, An-sa. He later served the Yuan court as commissioner of the Southern Capital's five-thousand household province. He is our lord's great-great-grandfather, now canonized as King Mok, with his tomb called Deung.

    His consort, of the Lee clan, daughter of Commander of the Thousand, Gong-suk, is now canonized as Filial Queen, with her tomb called Ung.

    The great-grandfather, Haeng-ri, inherited the fief of a thousand households, now canonized as King Ik, with his tomb called Chi. His consort, of the Choi clan of Deng-ju, is now canonized as Chaste Queen, with her tomb called Suk.

    The grandfather, given posthumous rank as Chief Counselor, named Chun, is now canonized as King Do, with his tomb called Ui. His consort, of the Park clan of Mun-ju, is canonized as Reverent Queen, with her tomb called Sun.

    The father, Honorable Duke overseeing Public Works, myriad-commander of Sak-bang, given posthumous rank of Gate Attendant, named Ja-chun, repeatedly distinguished himself in border campaigns, commanding tens of thousands. In the year Gyeongja, on the day Gapseul of the fourth moon, he fell ill and died at Sak-bang, aged forty-six. That year, on the day Byeongsin of the eighth moon, he was interred at the hill of Gwi-ju, east of Ham-ju. He is now canonized as King Hwan, with his tomb called Jungneung. His queen, of the Choi clan, daughter of the Chief Minister and Marquis of Yeong-heung, named Han-gi, is canonized as Exemplary Queen, with her tomb called Ho.

    Generation upon generation accumulated merit and virtue, laying the foundation of kingship. Goodness bloomed into blessing; the source runs deep, its current vast. From this was born the sage-king who established the great work. Heaven's care for the virtuous reaches its height.

    King Hwan took three consorts. The Exemplary Queen bore, besides our lord, one daughter, whom she married to Left Minister of the Three Excellencies Cho In-byeok. The Lee consort bore a son, Won-gye, who served the previous dynasty as Prince of Wan-san, and later died. The Princess An gave birth to a son by the Kim clan, named Ho, canonized as Baron of Ui-an.

    Our lord's consort, of the Han clan, daughter of the Chief Minister, named Kyeong, died first and was posthumously honored as Exemplary Queen, with her tomb called Je. She bore sons: Fang-wu, canonized as Prince of Jin-an; Fang-gwa, as Prince of Yeong-an; Fang-ui, as Prince of Ik-an; Fang-gan, as Prince of Hoe-an; and our lord's younger brother Taejong, canonized as Prince of Jeong-an. Fang-yeon died young and was posthumously granted the rank of Chief Scholar. Two daughters remain young.

    The second consort, of the Kang clan, daughter of the Director of the Three Excellencies, named Yun-sung, was canonized as Illustrious Queen. She bore Fang-beon, canonized as Prince of Mu-an, and young Fang-seok. A daughter married into the Lee clan of Gyeong-san, canonized as Prince of Heung-an.

    Prince Jin-an married the daughter of Chief Counselor Chi Yoon, begetting a son named Bok-geun, who holds the rank of Chief Scholar. Prince Yeong-an married the daughter of Gate Attendant Kim Cheon-seo. Prince Ik-an married the daughter of Chief Counselor Choi In-gyu, begetting Seok-geun, who holds the rank of Chief Scholar. Prince Hoe-an married the daughter of Chief Counselor Min Seon, begetting Maeng-jung, who holds the rank of Chief Scholar. Prince Jeong-an married the daughter of the Hanlin scholar Min Je. Prince Mu-an married the daughter of the Prince of Gwi-ui.

    Your servant observes that when emperors and kings arise, none have equaled the Zhou in the depth of ancestral accumulation and the breadth of their descendants' flourishing. From Duke of Zhou through countless generations to Kings Wen and Wu, they established their dynasty. Descendants multiplied like grasshoppers—truly this was the foundation of the Zhou's eight-hundred-year reign, achieved through the benevolent virtue of their ancestors.

    Now our realm, from the Sako down through King Hwan, has accumulated goodness across the ages. Our lord, possessed of brilliant wisdom and martial sagacity, has inherited the glorious deeds of his line and responded to Heaven's great blessings, opening an era of endless prosperity for ten thousand generations. His golden branches multiply and flourish—truly equal to the Zhou in glory. What is sown with such antiquity blossoms greatly; what is planted with such strength endures long.

    O, what magnificence! Your servant bows and offers this inscription:

    *Vast and luminous, the house of Lee,*
    *Foundation firm, roots deep below.*
    *From ancient Sako onward,*
    *Generation upon generation, virtue's song.*
    *The auspicious signs unfurled,*
    *Until King Hwan's age arrived,*
    *And our Sagacious Lord was born,*
    *To hold the Eastern realm entire.*
    *Heaven's mandate turned toward him;*
    *No war-coat worn, no battles fought.*
    *With people, he began anew,*
    *And spread his virtue's radiant light.*

    *The King spoke: In my unworthiness,*
    *I hold Heaven's bounty and grace—*
    *Truly by my ancestors' power,*
    *In nurturing blessings through the ages.*

    *He traced the ancient way,*
    *Conferring royal honor on the past.*
    *Hidden virtue reached its height;*
    *Its radiance shone forth unbidden.*
    *To the kindred of his house,*
    *He doubled blessing's weight.*
    *The root and branch alike*
    *Shall flourish for ten thousand ages.*

    *Behold that hill of Gwi-ju,*
    *Its summit rising high,*
    *The royal spirit gathers there,*
    *In glory without end.*

    *Your servant bows in reverence.*
    *This inscription speaks no flattery—*
    *Carved upon stone eternal,*
    *For all the world to see.*
  footnotes:
    - This stele was commissioned by King Taejo to honor his father, King Hwan (the title given posthumously to Yi Ja-chun), establishing the genealogical and moral foundation of the Joseon dynasty.
    - The reference to the five-hundred-year cycle derives from Mencius and reflects the Neo-Confucian philosophy that legitimate rule naturally emerges after prolonged moral decline.
